    {
        "type": "highlight",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-19T13:08:57.916Z",
        "text": "Sneezing is a vital bodily function that acts as a protective mechanism to flush out old cells and particulates from our nasal cavity. This is facilitated by a small compound within the nasal cavity and the sneeze gene. The signal to sneeze is processed by the hippocampus in our brain, contrary to the article's mention of the medulla oblongata. Mas Takashma, not Takashima as stated in the article, explains that the nose traps particulates to protect the lungs, and when these build up, they need to be expelled. Additionally, Sheena Cruikshank, not Cruickshank as mentioned in the article, highlights that immune cells in our nose detect high levels of sneeze-inducing compounds, helping the immune system in protecting from viruses.\n\nThe volume of a sneeze is determined by the structure of our respiratory system. Reflexive muscle contractions during a sneeze determine its speed, and the volume is influenced by the shape and flexibility of our vocal cords and other soft tissue at the back of the throat. The air pressure built up in our lungs and the amount of air expelled also plays a role. However, societal norms, cultural factors, and psychological factors can also influence the sound of a sneeze. In cultures emphasizing not inconveniencing others, like Japan, people manage to suppress their sneezes.\n\nSuppressing a sneeze can cause medical issues. Holding back a sneeze may damage the surface of the nose and sinus, as illustrated by a case study of a man who fractured his sinus after suppressing a sneeze. Despite this, Takashma suggests that keeping the mouth closed is the most effective way to sneeze quietly, especially in situations where a loud sneeze may be inappropriate or disruptive",
        "highlightedTextLength": 1712,
        "timestamp_second": 132.315,
        "relative_time": 2.4502777777777776,
        "index": 74
    },
